The fluorescence intensities of the CQDs at 325 nm excitation under different concentrations of Pb2+ were collected in Fig. 5
                        . One can see in Fig. 5a) that the emission peak intensity at 325 nm was enhanced after adding Pb2+, which implied the formation of a new complex of Pb2+ with the far excess CQDs. Therefore, the detection for Pb2+ could be realized by following the tracks of RRS intensity changes at 325 nm. Additionally, the effect of pH on the detection of Pb2+ by CQDs was investigated. As depicted in Fig. S9, the variation in RRS intensity before and after the addition of Pb2+ was the most significant at pH = 5.0, which was subjected to the following detection. In Fig. 5a), the RRS intensity exhibited a gradual increase at 325 nm, which could be attributed to the complexation of CQDs with Pb2+ increased the size and number of the scatter (Fig. S10) [14–17,57,58], and a slight fluorescence intensity decrease at 406 nm was observed for the heavy-atom effect of Pb2+ in the Pb2+ concentration ranged from 0-10 μM (inset). The RRS intensity changes of CQDs at 325 nm displayed a good linear relationship to the Pb2+ concentration in the range of 0–6 μM, and the corresponding linear calibration curve was collected in Fig. 5c. According to the formula LOD = KDSb/q1, where KD = 3 and q1 denoted the slope curve of the analytical calibration. Sb was the standard deviation of 10 measurements in the absence of Pb2+ (multiple measurement signals for blank samples), and the limit of detection (LOD) was produced to be as low as 0.42 μM, which confirmed a high sensitivity of the synthesized CQDs to Pb2+ detection (Table 1
                        ). [31,59–62]. Furthermore, the interaction between Pb2+ and CQDs was explored by FT-IR spectroscopy. As depicted in Fig. S11, the −CO peak of CQDs shifted from 1672 cm−1 to 1678 cm−1 after Pb2+ adsorption, and the symmetrical telescopic vibration of –COO at 1438 cm−1 weakened with transmittance decrease. These results suggested that Pb2+ primarily interacted with carboxyl functional groups on the surface of CQDs [63,64].
